{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640365"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17821"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17821"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.86,0.02,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9896"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24601"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lungs contain elastic fibres that contribute to their mechanical properties during breathing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes elastic recoil in the lungs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Outward force created by the diaphragm","Inward collapsing force due to elastic fibres and surface tension","Force that maintains constant alveolar volume","Force that expands the lungs during inspiration","Force generated by chest wall muscles during expiration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EElastic recoil refers to the \u003Cstrong\u003Einward collapsing force due to elastic fibres and surface tension\u003C/strong\u003E within the lungs. This force helps drive passive expiration and maintains appropriate lung volumes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diaphragm\u0027s contraction creates an \u003Cstrong\u003Eoutward force\u003C/strong\u003E that opposes elastic recoil during inspiration. Elastic recoil promotes alveolar emptying rather than maintaining a \u003Cstrong\u003Econstant alveolar volume\u003C/strong\u003E. Lung expansion during inspiration is driven by negative intrapleural pressure created by respiratory muscles, not by elastic recoil. Normal expiration is a passive process driven by elastic recoil; a \u003Cstrong\u003Eforce generated by chest wall muscles\u003C/strong\u003E is only required for forced expiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt functional residual capacity, the inward elastic recoil of the lungs is balanced by the outward recoil of the chest wall. This equilibrium determines the resting volume of the lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Elastic recoil is the tendency of the lungs to collapse inward due to elastic fibres and surface tension.","At functional residual capacity, the outward pull of the chest wall balances the inward pull of the lungs.","Loss of elastic recoil is a key feature of emphysema, leading to air trapping and hyperinflation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition. 2nd ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 7; p. 120."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T14:50:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:50:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10535"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t